<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="68" pageId="3" pageNumber="67" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1554,2028]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,152,452]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="68" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,1554,1578]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="67" reason="1">Description.</emphasis>
Male. Wingspan 
<quantity box="[526,643,1554,1577]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.7" metricValueMax="4.8" metricValueMin="4.6" pageId="3" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="47.0" valueMax="48.0" valueMin="46.0">46–48 mm</quantity>
; 
<emphasis box="[655,721,1554,1577]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">Head:</emphasis>
Labial palpi black, curved upward, third segment shorter than first two. Frons, vertex, scape, antenna and pectinations black. 
<emphasis box="[785,871,1589,1612]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">Thorax:</emphasis>
Patagia and tegulae entirely black with long scales. Thorax dorsally black with long scales, ventrally black with orange and yellow scales at the insertion areas of each pair of legs. These areas are merged with the middle and posterior pairs. Legs entirely black. 
<emphasis box="[1123,1233,1658,1681]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">Abdomen:</emphasis>
Black ringed with yellow with the basal tergites covered with long black scales similar to those of the thorax. Black ventrally. Anal tuft black. 
<emphasis box="[224,327,1728,1751]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">Forewing</emphasis>
: Length: 
<quantity box="[434,514,1728,1751]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="3" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="22.0">22 mm</quantity>
. Ground colour light brown, slightly darker in the subterminal area. Venation darker and contrasting. Basal third of the costa yellowish. Reniform spot black. Ventral surface entirely brown, reniform spot slightly marked. Fringe brown. 
<emphasis box="[506,620,1797,1820]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">Hindwing:</emphasis>
Whitish, with strongly contrasting brown venation. Anal margin slightly darker. Fringe brown. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[398,560,1832,1856]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[578,658,1832,1855]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–11" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1415,1439]" captionTargetBox="[167,1433,211,1371]" captionTargetId="figure-336@3.[151,1436,194,1391]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 10–11. Dorsal view of male genitalia. 10. Pseudopharus reniforma holotype (prep gen B. Vincent no. BV 398). 11. Pseudopharus cornelia (prep gen B. Vincent no. BV 409)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5246083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5246083/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) – Uncus straight, very long and thin. Tegumen short, formed by two ridges. Vinculum formed by two arms, thin and right. A broad, foliated and slightly sclerotized band along the dorsal face of these arms. The apex of this band, round and finely spinous, reaches the base of the uncus. Valves wide at the base, tapering significantly at the height of the uncus in the form of a long thin cylinder. Inner surface covered with numerous long setae. On the costa is an elongated ampulla parallel to the valves. The structure is more sclerotized and slightly shorter and the apex is marked with four sclerotized teeth. Sacculus very broad and ventrally bent. Transtilla reduced and formed of two small sclerotized ribs. Penis short, abruptly narrowed at the middle with one half slightly curved and apically flared (Fig. 12). Caecum penis reduced. Vesica very large, cylindrical and bearing short diverticula without cornuti. Female: unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="68" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,152,452]" pageId="4" pageNumber="68">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,255,279]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="68" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Druce, 1906)" baseAuthorityName="Druce" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[657,1072,256,279]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Pseudopharus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cornelia">
<emphasis box="[657,907,256,279]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="68">Pseudopharus cornelia</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Druce, H." box="[925,1064,256,279]" pageId="4" pageNumber="68" pagination="77 - 94" refId="ref2325" refString="Druce, H. (1906) Descriptions of some new species of Heterocera from tropical South America. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, (7), 18, 77 - 94." type="journal article" year="1906">Druce, 1906</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, described from Santo Domingo, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,200,290,313]" name="Peru" pageId="4" pageNumber="68">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[214,279,290,313]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1723,1747]" captionTargetBox="[166,1412,966,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-486@1.[151,1436,937,1700]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Adult dorsal view. 1. Bernathomonus postrosea male holotype. 2. Bernathomonus aureopuncta male. 3. Pseudopharus reniforma male holotype. 4. Pseudopharus cornelia male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5246079" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5246079/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="68">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), but it can be distinguished from that species by the following differences: light blue dots on the occiput and at the insertion area on the wings. White median dots on the posterior edge of the thorax, forewing shorter than 
<quantity box="[1354,1433,325,348]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="68" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 mm</quantity>
. Thorax ventrally black, hindwing with costa, apex and black on the outer edge. In the male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[1228,1304,360,383]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–11" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1415,1439]" captionTargetBox="[167,1433,211,1371]" captionTargetId="figure-336@3.[151,1436,194,1391]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 10–11. Dorsal view of male genitalia. 10. Pseudopharus reniforma holotype (prep gen B. Vincent no. BV 398). 11. Pseudopharus cornelia (prep gen B. Vincent no. BV 409)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5246083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5246083/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="68">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
and 13), the uncus apex is club-shaped with an apical point, the valves are large with a bifurcated apex, the cuculus is translucent and rounded, the ampulla are as long as valves, marked ventrally by numerous spines, bent at the apex.
</paragraph>
